import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data=pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Immigration\\immigration_1.csv")

count_positive = 0
count_negative = 0
count_neutral = 0

for sentiment in data['sentiment']:
    if sentiment == 'Positive':
        count_positive += 1
    else:
        count_negative += 1
total=len(data)
positive_response= (count_positive / total) * 100
negative_response = (count_negative / total) * 100
myexplode = [0.2, 0]
y=[positive_response,negative_response]
plt.pie(y,labels=[str(round(positive_response,2))+"%",str(round(negative_response,2))+"%"],explode = myexplode, shadow = True,colors=["g","r"])
plt.title("Check IN tweet % distribution")
plt.legend(["positive","negative"])
plt.show()

LDA for positive tweets¶

In [3]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the positive reviews data
positive_reviews = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Immigration\\immigration_1 - Copy.csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = positive_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Extend the default English stop words list with custom stop words
stop_words = list(text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS) + custom_stop_words

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)
for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: 12, stuck, boarding, contact, improve, help, screening, air, form, india
Topic 2: queue, happen, quick, crowded, security, hello, international, spent, hours, time
Topic 3: office, ask, officer, better, travel, india, know, country, test, sir
Topic 4: able, officer, recently, efficient, felt, kannada, happy, staff, time, long
Topic 5: customs, smooth, aug, help, process, let, baggage, flight, blrairport, thank

Observation on positive tweet¶

  • ### The Indian government has taken steps to improve the air travel experience for passengers, such as improving the air travel form and making the security and customs processes more efficient.
  • ### Airport staff are generally helpful and efficient.

Recommendations:¶

  • ### Continue to improve the air travel experience for passengers by streamlining procedures, using technology, and training staff on customer service.
  • ### Recognize and reward staff members who provide excellent customer service.

Word Cloud for positive tweets¶

In [4]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Create a word cloud object
wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_font_size=50)

# Check the type of the topics variable
if isinstance(topics, list):
    # Convert the topics variable to a list of strings
    topics = [" ".join(topic) for topic in topics]

# Generate the word cloud
wc.generate(" ".join(topics))

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.imshow(wc)
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Top Words in Positive Reviews")
plt.show()

LDA for Negative tweets¶

In [5]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation
from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the negative reviews data
negative_reviews = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Immigration\\immigration_1 - Copy (2).csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = negative_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Convert the custom stop words to a list
custom_stop_words = list(custom_stop_words)

# Extend the default English stop words list with custom stop words
stop_words = list(text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS) + custom_stop_words

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for negative reviews)
for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: allow, urgent, flying, salman, khan, kindly, hours, kannada, flight, officer
Topic 2: stranded, sir, sfo, service, experience, exit, staff, minutes, 45, going
Topic 3: delhi, staff, big, screening, pass, fast, wait, feb, time, passengers
Topic 4: lookout, court, india, circular, thursday, aakar, amp, stopped, cbi, patel
Topic 5: asked, delhi, feel, night, domestic, wait, security, worst, hours, mumbai

Observation on negative tweet¶

  • ### Passenger was stranded at SFO for 45 minutes due to negative service experience.
  • ### Passengers at Delhi Airport are facing long wait times for security screening.
  • ### Passenger felt that the security wait time at Delhi Airport on a domestic flight was the worst they have ever experienced.

Recommendations:¶

  • ### Airports should improve their communication with passengers, especially those who are experiencing negative experiences. This could be done by providing multilingual signage, having bilingual staff available, and using other communication tools such as gestures and body language.
  • ### Airports should review their security processes and make changes to improve efficiency and reduce wait times. This could be done by increasing the number of security staff, improving the layout of security checkpoints, and using more efficient screening technologies.
  • ### Airports should provide adequate training to staff to ensure that they are able to provide quality service to all passengers. This could include training on customer service skills, cultural awareness, and security procedures.
